{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"Arjun's Blog","author":"Arjun Munji"}},"markdownRemark":{"id":"edc9ba12-ad9f-58e0-b5f0-4ef7d6f42ba3","excerpt":"Over the last week, I built a fun ™  and cool ™  web app to draw doodles and simple drawings.\nI appropriately named it  Sketch . You can check it out here…","html":"<p>Over the last week, I built a fun™ and cool™ web app to draw doodles and simple drawings.\nI appropriately named it <strong>Sketch</strong>.</p>\n<p>You can check it out here: <a href=\"https://sketch.arjun.ninja\">https://sketch.arjun.ninja</a></p>\n<h2>Why</h2>\n<p>I got the idea for Sketch while I was checking out the <a href=\"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Canvas_API\">article</a> for HTML5 Canvas on MDN.\nNow why was I doing that? Because I recently completed Wes Bos’ <a href=\"https://javascript30.com\">JavaScript30</a> course (great course btw, highly recommend!) and used Canvas element in one of the course lessons.\nI was immediately blown away by its capabilities and potential.\nSo to dig deeper, I scoured the internet for resources and found myself on MDN.</p>\n<h2>Process</h2>\n<p>First, I noted down the functionality my app would provide. writing it down helped me focus and build a <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minimum_viable_product\">Minimum Viable Product</a>.</p>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/blog/static/ef41a98dbfa08c0f24572f18f4113d44/2d7b7/user-stories.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block;  max-width: 590px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 82.05944798301485%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;\"\n        alt=\"User Stories\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/blog/static/ef41a98dbfa08c0f24572f18f4113d44/f8fb9/user-stories.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/blog/static/ef41a98dbfa08c0f24572f18f4113d44/e8976/user-stories.jpg 148w,\n/blog/static/ef41a98dbfa08c0f24572f18f4113d44/63df2/user-stories.jpg 295w,\n/blog/static/ef41a98dbfa08c0f24572f18f4113d44/f8fb9/user-stories.jpg 590w,\n/blog/static/ef41a98dbfa08c0f24572f18f4113d44/85e3d/user-stories.jpg 885w,\n/blog/static/ef41a98dbfa08c0f24572f18f4113d44/2d7b7/user-stories.jpg 942w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<p>I started by building whatever I had learned during the Canvas course.\nWith little effort, I had a canvas to draw on and a function to listen to mouse events and translate them to ink on the canvas.</p>\n<p>Here’s an initial UI mockup:</p>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/blog/static/d3bd2d010987f2d771130d04277de44a/8257f/ui-mockup.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block;  max-width: 590px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 134.18693982074262%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;\"\n        alt=\"UI Mockup\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/blog/static/d3bd2d010987f2d771130d04277de44a/f8fb9/ui-mockup.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/blog/static/d3bd2d010987f2d771130d04277de44a/e8976/ui-mockup.jpg 148w,\n/blog/static/d3bd2d010987f2d771130d04277de44a/63df2/ui-mockup.jpg 295w,\n/blog/static/d3bd2d010987f2d771130d04277de44a/f8fb9/ui-mockup.jpg 590w,\n/blog/static/d3bd2d010987f2d771130d04277de44a/8257f/ui-mockup.jpg 781w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<p>I then added a colour palette, a brush width selector, and a multi-colour brush. The multi-colour brush is my favorite.</p>\n<p><video autoplay loop muted width=\"100%\" preload=\"auto\" playsinline src=\"/blog/sketch-color-selection-ff0503bc8bbee531ed7580a31950f1c7.mp4\"> </video></p>\n<p>I then added touch and multi-touch, with the help of MDN’s excellent <a href=\"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Touch_events\">guide</a> to adding touch input to canvases. There was only one feature remaining in my list: Saving sketches as images.</p>\n<p>For this, I used the canvas API’s <code class=\"language-text\">toDataURL()</code> method to convert the canvas to a base64 encoded string of <code class=\"language-text\">image/png</code> type, which I then set as the <code class=\"language-text\">href</code> in my download link element.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"html\"><pre class=\"language-html\"><code class=\"language-html\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">&lt;</span>a</span> <span class=\"token attr-name\">href</span><span class=\"token attr-value\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">=</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">\"</span>#<span class=\"token punctuation\">\"</span></span> <span class=\"token attr-name\">download</span><span class=\"token attr-value\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">=</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">\"</span>drawing.png<span class=\"token punctuation\">\"</span></span> <span class=\"token attr-name\">onclick</span><span class=\"token attr-value\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">=</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">\"</span>saveImage()<span class=\"token punctuation\">\"</span></span> <span class=\"token attr-name\">class</span><span class=\"token attr-value\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">=</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">\"</span>action<span class=\"token punctuation\">\"</span></span><span class=\"token punctuation\">></span></span>\n  Download sketch\n<span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">&lt;/</span>a</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">></span></span></code></pre></div>\n<p>The <code class=\"language-text\">download</code> attribute triggers a save dialogue in the browser when the link is clicked.\nUnfortunately, this hack was of no use in mobile browsers because apparently mobile browsers don’t automatically decode base64 strings.</p>\n<p>I said screw it, ship it. And that’s how I got to my MVP, two days after I started from scratch.\nI launched the website on GitHub Pages and got good reviews from my cool friends.</p>\n<p><strong>This is v1:</strong></p>\n<p><video autoplay loop muted width=\"100%\" preload=\"auto\" playsinline src=\"/blog/sketch-v1-1053b590eeb152b52601221ecfe648e9.mp4\"></video></p>\n<!-- But the lack of mobile save option still bugged me.\nMeanwhile, I thought of another feature:\n**A unique share URL for every sketch**.\n\n## Sketch v2\n\n*To be continued...* -->","frontmatter":{"title":"How I Built Sketch","date":"April 16, 2017","tags":["projects"]}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/how-i-built-sketch/","previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/jadoo/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Jadoo"}},"next":{"fields":{"slug":"/2018-in-review/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"2018 In Review"}}}}